<TITLE> Thousands pay last respects to Jyoti Basu </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KOLKATA, Jan 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Tens of thousands of mourners waving red flags walked through the streets of Kolkata to catch a final glimpse of communist patriarch Jyoti Basu, who died at the weekend. Basu, whose pragmatic politics twice brought him close to becoming prime minister, died on Sunday at the age of 95. He gained fame leading West Bengal for almost a quarter century, the longest-serving chief minister in Indian political history. As Basu's teary-eyed followers poured out into the streets, the city came to a halt. People jostled for space in long serpentine queues and many sang communist revolutionary songs. "You sleep in peace, we will keep awake" read a banner carried by one of his followers. Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, ruling Congress chief Sonia Gandhi and Bharatiya Janata Party leader Lal Krishna Advani were among those who paid floral tributes to the leader at the state assembly. Basu was later given a 21-gun salute at a prominent city park. In keeping with his wishes, Basu's body would be handed over to a state-run medical college hospital for resea
